'''Iztok Puc''' (14 September 1966 &ndash; 20 October 2011) was a [[Slovenia]]n [[team handball|handball]] player who is considered as one of the greatest players in history.<ref name="rtvslo1">{{cite web | url = http://www.rtvslo.si/sport/rokomet/slovo-rokometne-legende-puc-izgubil-bitko-z-rakom/268840 | title = Slovo rokometne legende: Puc izgubil bitko z rakom | author = M.L. | date = 20 october 2011 | publisher = rtvslo.si | language = Slovene | accessdate = 21 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.24sata.hr/rukomet/ivano-balic-nadam-se-da-cete-napuniti-arenu-i-pomoci-iztoku-239197 | title = Bali<U+0107>: Puc je bio najbolji lijevi bek, imao je sve, <U+0161>ut, pregled... | author = Alen Besedi<U+0107> | date = 20 october 2011 | publisher = 24sata.hr | language = Croatian | accessdate = 21 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gnkdinamo.hr/preminula-hrvatska-sportska-legenda-iztok-puc.html | title = Preminula hrvatska sportska legenda - Iztok Puc | author = GNK Dinamo Zagreb | date = 20 october 2011 | publisher = gnkdinamo.hr | language = Croatian | accessdate = 21 October 2011}}</ref> He is the only handball player that has represented three different countries at the [[Summer Olympics]] - [[SFR Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]], [[Croatia]] and [[Slovenia]].<ref name="rtvslo1"/><ref name="vjesnik1">{{cite web | url = http://www.vjesnik.hr/Article.aspx?ID=30396EE0-A211-44A1-ADE9-1B44E7B40804 | title = Iztok Puc izgubio bitku s te<U+0161>kom bole<U+0161><U+0107>u | author = Vjesnik | date = 20 october 2011 | publisher = vjesnik.hr | language = Croatian | accessdate = 21 October 2011}}</ref> At the 60th anniversary of the Handball Federation of Slovenia in 2009 he was chosen as the best left back and the best player in Slovenian handball history.<ref name="vjesnik1"/><ref name="rzs1">{{cite web | url = http://www.rokometna-zveza.si/info/10 | title = Slovo rokometne legende: Puc izgubil bitko z rakom | author = Rokometna Zveza Slovenije (RZS) | date = | publisher = rokometna-zveza.si | language = Slovene | accessdate = 21 October 2011}}</ref>

==Club career==
He played for [[RK Celje]] and [[Prule 67]] from Slovenia, [[RK Zagreb]] from Croatia, and [[RK Borac Banja Luka]] from Bosnia and Herzegovina.

==International career==
His first taste of international glory came at the 1987 Youth World Championship where Yugoslavia won gold.<ref name="sportsport">{{cite web | url = http://www.sportsport.ba/rukomet/iztok-puc-1966---2011/66502 | title = IZTOK PUC 1966 - 2011 | author = M. Maksimovi<U+0107> | date = 20 October 2011 | publisher = sportsport.ba | language = Bosnian | accessdate = 21 October 2011}}</ref> One year later he won a bronze medal with the [[Yugoslavia national handball team|Yugoslav senior team]] at the [[1988 Summer Olympics]] in [[Seoul]]. His played his last game for Yugoslavia at the [[1990 World Men's Handball Championship|1990 World Championship]] where his team finished fourth.<ref name="sportsport"/> After the [[breakup of Yugoslavia]] in 1991 he played for the [[Croatia national handball team|Croatian team]] which won the gold medal at the [[1996 Summer Olympics]] in [[Atlanta]].<ref name=sports-ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/pu/iztok-puc-1.html | title=Profile: Iztok Puc |publisher=sports-reference.com |accessdate=17 January 2009}}</ref> He won two other medals with Croatia, a bronze medal at the [[1994 European Men's Handball Championship|1994 European Championship]] and a silver medal at the [[1995 World Men's Handball Championship|1995 World Championship]]. In late 1990s he switched his national side allegiance and decided in favour of Slovenia, the country of his birth. He played for the [[Slovenia national handball team|Slovenian team]] at the [[2000 Summer Olympics]] in [[Sydney]] with the team finishing eighth. Slovenia qualified for the Sydney tournament after finishing fifth at the [[2000 European Men's Handball Championship|2000 European Championship]]. The placement match for fifth place was played in [[Zagreb]] against the host nation and Puc's former team, Croatia. Puc was one of the best players of the game and Slovenia won the match 25<U+2013>24, thus securing the last available spot at the 2000 Olympics.

He has made a total of 97 appearances for Yugoslavia and 34 for Slovenia.<ref name="rzs1"/>

==Illness and death==
In early 2011, Puc was diagnosed with lung cancer and succumbed to illness on 20 October 2011, days short of the [[EHF Champions League]] game between Zagreb and [[FC Barcelona Handbol|Barcelona]] and two weeks before ''a day of handball'' in [[Celje]] where two games, between Croatian squad composed of players that won a gold medal at the 1996 Olympics and the Slovenian squad that played at the 2000 Olympics and between the current squads of Slovenia and Celje, for the purpuse that the revenue of all three games is donated to Puc and his family as the financial aid for his treatment. After his death, the revenue of all three games will be transferred to Puc's family nevertheless. He is survived by his son, Borut, a tennis player who resides in Florida, where Puc spent the last few years of his life.

